description.text:

Features:

  • up to 4 thermistors (one onboard)
  • up to 3 fans,
  • 12-24V power supply,
  • separate power supply for bed, hotend and rest electronic

EAGLE files, BOM (for large version, but 99% electronic components have same), photos.

  1. Add 10uF capacitor between GND and RESET pin

EXP1 on DUE3DOM = EXP2 on SmartController
EXP2 on DUE3DOM = EXP1 on SmartController

This is rev. A, but tested with a lot of people.

description.text: UPDATED 02/09/14 - and now, for something completely different ... http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:245431 UPDATED 03/07/13 - thank you to all who "liked" my project, but if you are serious about building one, you really should consider building this one: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:20398 It's a great "Thing" and is complete. A year later I went back to build mine and found it to be incomplete This is my version of a semi-completely printable spherebot drawn using google sketchup. I started out with the intent to make it completely printable, but Easter is coming and at the rate I'm going, I would be lucky to have it done in time for drawing on Christmas ornaments,so I've abandoned the "completely" printable part and used 1/4" rods for the frame and M3's for mounting the steppers and 5/16 bolt for the egg cup holder. If you download the "Spherebot all files" file, you get the sketchups, STL's, Gcodes all in one I have printed it as seen in the pics, however, I have already detected a potential flaw in that I'm only using 3 1/4" threaded rods for the frame and that missing 4th corner is causing my egg to skew a bit when mounted. My problem is, if I add a 4th rod, it interferes with the position of the pen ... I think I can work around the 4th corner missing so I've spent most of my time trying to figure out what's wrong with my wiring cause the best I can get is the egg spinning and the servo lifting/dropping the pen ...

I guess most people will not be able to print the full set in one session. I can't do it on my Prusa Mendel. But one way or another, you'll need to print the 2 sides (stepper side, bearing side) and the back as well as the egg cups from thing:13960 and use the pen holder from thing:7988 (Thanks and kudos to rrhb and berserker for their great work on which this is based. Not to mention zaggo (thing:7656)
I cut 1/4 rod at 7" lengths, then threaded them thru the stepperback.stl and then attached the sides. This is a pain because you have to spin the threaded rod with your fingers. In retrospect, it's just better to use smooth rod cause the holes will fit tight enough to hold in place, but then, I'm not the brightest star in the galaxy.
I used a 5/16" bolt and a skateboard bearing on the one side of the frame
Now, if I can figure out why my electronics don't want to do what I want them to do...
anyway, I hope you enjoy it and if you get one working, let me know cause I'd sure like to see someone be successful. OR if you improve this design and goodness knows that should be easy, let me know and I'll use yours.

Join the EBS Group

http://www.thingiverse.com/groups/ebs-electronic-building-system
and you are allways up to date with all news, assembling-tipps updates and new parts.

Update 28.Nov.2016

Planning your own circuits for EBS
Building with EBS sometimes needs a little bit planning.
To do this, i made a library for TinyCAD. Now you can make a detailed Plan for the modules and how to make the connections, before you (or another person) puts the Modules together and does the wiring.
You must have installed TinyCad, whitch is free software. Download and save the EBS-Library to your PC. Add the library to TinyCad and you'r done.

In case of new modules and updates the newest library (EBS.TCLib) can allways be downloaded here.

Attention: You need TinyCAD, NOT Tinker-CAD!

'Silent' Update 27.Nov.2016

For module 'BlockBat' i found out, it's best to glue the batteryclip to the ground and click the battery on it with the contacts down. So you need 2 holes for the wires of the clip. These are done with this little update of the scad-files.

Update 26.Nov.2016

For my printouts, i had to do much work after printing to get good fitting parts, becaus my printer is not very exact.
So i put here a second OpenSCAD file, which produces modules with higher tolerances.

Low tolerances: US_BK_Schaltung-K.scad
High torerances: US_BK_Schaltung-K2.scad

In case of new things are uploaded, allways bozh of the files you will find updated here.

Remark: The downloadable stl-files for EBS, are allways produced with the low-tolerance-scad-file.
So, if you want high-tolerance-modules, you must use the scad-file. Give it a try. It's not complicated, but very intuitive. And, of course, OpenSCAD is free.

Welcome

to my brand new 2nd version of the Electronic Building System.

Using this system, you can build circuits, strongly based to a circuit-diagram.
Good built, the function and wireing of the circuit is much more obvious, the overview so much better, than in a circuit, built on a common breadboard. This is very important for children and beginners!
The advantage of a common breadboard, the simple contacting, is , of course, fully taken over to this system!

Approvements to old system:

  • Better and stronger fitting
  • Contact-System is very easy and works great, and, of course, without any soldering.
    Klick on Post-Printing for details
  • Will soon be continued with new parts as DIL8 for NE555 or OpAmp, with Spools, Potis,
    78xx, variable capacitor, ... Let's build a little Radio, a transmitter (with very little power),
    to hear your music in the radio next room, some blinking LED's, and much more...

The web is full with tons of educational and fascinating circuit diagrams, electronic parts are fairly cheap. Have fun... There are almost no limits, using this system.

All published data are denied for any commercial use!
You can print and edit all data for privat use only.

The old system (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1885504) will not be continued (but also not deleted)! Parts of old and new system are NOT compatible!

The contact-system and the way to assemble a block is described in Post-Printing.

Assembling the blocks

After printing, your first job is to prepare the contacts.
You need rows of common precision contacts, which are also used for contacting dil-ic's.

For each contact of you block, you will need a row of 3 sockets.

Use two drops of solder to connect the 3 sockets and solder about 1-2cm wire to the middle socket.
Also, read the description of ArizonaClark in the comments, perhaps you will find his procedure easyer for you,

Use a good drop of Glue to fit it into the printed socket.
Do this for each contact of your block.

Sorry, the printout had to be verry hasty. Your 3d-printed blocks schould look a lot better!

Put the electronic part in place and solder it to the wire and cut the spare wires.
That's all. Your new block is ready to be used in your circuit.

Common switching-wire will fit perfectly into the sockets, and for each contact of your block, you can pusch 3 wires in. If that's not enough, make a special Y-wire or use a "Verbindung"-block.

Designed with OpenSCAD

As usual, i designed all parts with OpenSCAD.
The source file is included, so you can adjust everything and you can print of course several parts at the same time.

The source file and all stl-files are not allowed to be commercial used!
If you want to do so, contact me and we will find a satisfying solution.

Hello! This is a simple hand tool to cut circles. You can adjust the distance from 10mm to 100mm, with 1mm increments. A gradation indicates the distance of the needle to the blade, but use a ruler to verify the radius. It uses a standard hobby blade (x-acto) that slides into a slot. It's press-fit for me, but if the blade is slightly loose, you can glue it in place to make sure it doesn't move. To install it, insert a nail in the blade's oblong hole and push it through. To install the needle, cut a pushpin and fix it in the needle-holding part using crazy glue. To print the parts on a FDM machine, it's better to place them all in an upright position (like they are on pictures). Update: new blade cover added

title: Fabrikator mini magnetic print bed bracket

description.text:
Magnetic attached brackets for the print bed on the fabrikator mini, one stays attached to the printer, the other to the bed, 3 variations can be generated depending if you want keying or not, designed around 6x4mm cylindrical magnets.

I'm using a keyed set for the back brackets and a non keyed set for the front and this is working really well :)

You will find you need to adjust the z axis, I'm probably going to design a better z axis end stop mount as this has highlight how much of a pain in the arse the stock design is.

Ok, some installation instructions :D

Installing the brackets to the bed is fairly straight forward, so I won't cover that but installing the brackets to the carriage and installing the magnets can be "fun"

First things first,with the magnets you may need to drill the holes to get them in, this can make them a little loose, if this is the case, push the magnet half way through the front and apply some superglue the back before pushing the magnets flush again, this will make sure some of it gets down the sides and gets a good fix.

Installing the brackets to the bed can be a pain, to do this I removed the front (for access), then removed the clips holding in the smooth rods on one side, I could then slide them out to release the carriage.

Re-assembly is the opposite of dis-assembly :D

Getting it on and off of the belt is a pain.

Edit: 19/11/2016

Installed the brackets and made a test print, so far so good (but don't forget to adjust the z-azis :D)

Edit: 20/11/2016

Works as planned, no major issues, it has reinforced the need for a better z-axis endstop arrangement though, that screw is a pita to get too and it does not stay put for long, something attached to the front or side panel makes a lot more sense.

description.text:
Power Supply cover, Power Switch, Power cord socket for the newer model Anet A8, Hesine, Senhai, M505, Omni etc printers. This cover will work with the uxcell S-250-12 20 Amp PSU linked below. I only have access to the Anet A8 so I am not sure if other manufacturers have switched out power supplies with the same wider one Anet is using. I am also not sure if the Anet A2, or A6 use the same one as the A8.

This cover is designed to use a switched and fused IEC 320 C14 similar to the one linked below, which can be found for around $1 off of Ebay if you're fine with a longer shipping time.

No support material is needed and can be mounted securely with a single m3 screw on the right side of the PSU, though some hot glue can easilly be added if needed.

Links

Note: For Ebay search links make sure that the one you order matches the one on Amazon, or it likely will not work with this part.

Ebay Search: http://ebay.to/2jkM2ec

Uxcell 20 Amp Power Supply:
Amazon: http://amzn.to/2iNlGyu
Ebay Search: http://ebay.to/2iKYDGA

Update #1 (11/20/2016)

A new model with the correct screw hole location for newer Anet printers has replaced the old file with the incorrect hole location. If this location is incorrect for your printer, or the width is incorrect please message me and I'll work with you to get a new working model up. I have also uploaded another model with a thinner clipping area for the switch/plug combo unit I have linked to on Amazon, as well as a wiring diagram for said switch. If you have any problems feel free to message me/comment and I'll reply as soon as I can.

title: Screwless & silent mini ITX computer case

description.text:
UPDATE:
v1.01:

  • Added vent slots
  • Improved catches
  • Improved clearance for NIC ethernet cable removal
    Please let me know your results if you print it!

I designed this case to be a mini ITX pfSense router containing a discrete Intel NIC, an SSD and a slim 12cm fan.

It's quite neat and very easy to put together - only 2 halves that slide together - the front and the back!

Small printer friendly - each half footprint is approx 20cm x 8.6cm and height 11cm for the taller half.

Great as a small factor desktop, home theatre PC or a router/firewall.

The motherboard and NIC together slide into grooves, and are quite sturdy.

The the locking tabs might need some tweaking.

In my original V1 design, the tabs snapped off but the case is still usable. Since then I improved the design but haven't printed the new version myself so let me know your results.

It also has holes in the back for 2x SMA headers if you need to run a wifi module (may need to enlarge these - I didn't end up using them so can't comment on fit).

It's designed to fit a standard mini ITX backplate, so in theory any motherboard will fit provided the heatsink isn't too tall and the Pico PSU has clearance.

I used a 16mm LED push button as a on/off switch (overkill but looks nice).

Asus J1900I-C Quad core celeron

Thanks for your comment.
Yes it does disrupt airflow a lot - but the motherboard's TDP is super low and it's designed to be passively cooled - so even the fraction of the total airflow that gets past the ssd is more than the system needs. I spec'd the fan to be as large as possible to compensate for this.
The SSD is only there because it's dead space otherwise. If I put the SSD below the motherboard, the case would be larger because of the upright NIC.
If no NIC, it would be massively smaller overall and I would probably remove the fan all together!

description.text: This retainer saves time and eliminates frustration when mounting Hiwin MGN-12C/MGN-12H carriages back onto the linear rails. These 12mm linear rails are typically used in Kossel based printers and although the carriages have a wire retainer it does not do a good job in preventing the balls from escaping. Note: The no-name carriages vary wildly in dimensions (I found a difference of almost 0.5mm between two carriages in the same set) so you might have to scale before print. This part is designed to have 9.25mm clearance between the retainer wires.

Print at 0.2 layer or less and 50% infill.
  • Load the printed part inside the carriage
  • Align the carriage with the rail
  • Slide the carriage on the rail while keeping pressure on the plastic retainer
Last week we published a Soldier: 76 helmet that had some embedded electronics. Rather than have removable batteries, we opted to build in a wireless charging set!

Notes:

ChargingCradle: Print in white
Cap: Print in white
StickerGrey: Print in Grey
StickerOrange: Print in Orange

Assembly after Printing

You'll need three things to complete this set:

  • Inductive Charging Set
  • Panel Mount Barrel Jack
  • 9VDC Power Supply
  1. Solder two wires to the positive and ground pins of the barrel jack. These should be long enough to pass through the base of the cradle.
  2. Insert the nut of the panel mount jack into the cradle, then screw the barrel jack into place.
  3. Grab the transmitting half of the inductive charging set, and pass the chip through the opening in the base of the cradle. See the photos above if you're unsure.
  4. Solder the connections from the barrel jack to the inductive charging chip. Make sure you don't mix up + an -!
  5. Slide the chip into the base of the cradle, while letting the copper coil wires pass through the slot at the bottom.
  6. Press the coil into place. You made need a dab of superglue to fix it there!
  7. Glue the cap into place.

And that's it! Your Soldier: 76 headset will now wirelessly charge! Good luck!

comments.text: This was due to warping from ABS. I assume it split roughly every 5 cm? ABS has high shrinkage and high glass transition temperature, thus generating high thermal strain. This strain will add up until it is higher than the lamination force generated by welding the layers on top of each other. You would need a heatet chamber at around 70 °C to avoid this for ABS. PLA is really brittle and might break quite fast (while using the case). I always use PET for an application like this. Easy to print like PLA, almost no warping and really good toughness.

comments.text: I just printed this is PLA and came out fantastic.  I would like to try PET.  Would you be willing to share your settings when printing in PET?
comments.author: krosstoph

comments.text:
Depends on the kind of PET you have. There are some kinds printable between 190-220 °C and some between 230-250 °C depending on the modifications they saw. I usually use the top end of the required temperature range. I like using large nozzles, thick layers and high speeds when possible. This design would be perfect for that, being just a box without intricate features or curves.
In this case I would use up to 275 °C (for the PET with max 250 °C) with a 0.8 mm nozzle (e3d v6 HotEnd, not the volcano), aorund 40 mm/s speed on my 3 year old Prusa I3 and 0.6 mm layer height in the vertical sections. 0.2 or 0.3 mm layers for the rounded corners. Since the volume flow would be a third to a half here, I would adjust the temperature to around 255 °C.
Whenever possible, I like to avoid the use of a fan cooling my print and preferably adjust the temperature to get better layer adhesions. All the settings stated are therefor with fan OFF. If you use a fan, you might be able to use the 275 °C throughout the whole print, but you should test all this yourself. In such "big" prints with round corners, I always use a brim of around 10mm to avoid warping on the edges and I print PET on Kapton tape.
Also try to use dry PET, since it is hygroscopic. The absorbed water hydrolizes the PET-molecules when passing through the nozzle which will make your print more brittle, thus loosing the advantage of being more ductile or tough than PLA.

All of this depends on your setup: Extruder, HotEnd, Nozzle diameter etc. Can you describe what you are using? I can give you better advice then. comments.text: I'm using @ESUN 3mmm PET-G Filament (https://www.amazon.com/gp/product/B00MVIQ6QG/ref=oh_aui_search_detailpage?ie=UTF8&psc=1). I'm printing on a Ultimaker 2+ with a .4mm extruder but I also have a .25mm nose I could switch to if necessary. I do have a heated bed on my printer.
comments.author: krosstoph

comments.text:
With the .4mm nozzle you should use no more than .32mm layer height. You can use the max recommended temperature on your HotEnd, which as I see it is 260 °C for your filament. If your Ultimaker can hanlde speeds above 60 mm/s I would use 270 °C, but keep in mind, that the outmost perimeters are usually printed slower. The Temp advice is for the real speed on the outmost perimeter considering the thin wall of the part and it will mostly be built by perimeters and almost no infill. If it is reduced there to less than 60 mm/s, just use 260°C. Use at least 85 °C on your heatbed and use a brim of a minimum width of 5mm (adjust your number of "Outlines" according to your extrusion width). On the first layer, check that the brim is well attached to the outline of your part, else it will not prevent warping of the corners.
PS: Another tip on printing parts like this, which have thin vertical walls: Try adjusting your extrusion width and perimeter count, such that you dont get infill inbetweend the perimeters of the vertical walls. You can incrementally adjust the parameters in S3D and check in the print preview if there are gaps left. Find the maximum amount of perimeters that fit first (you can calculate that by wallthickness/2*perimterwidth) and then go higher on the extrusion width. Going lower is not recommended.
